Yes, it is possible to use ASP.NET Core MVC without Razor view pages and replace them with regular .html pages that GET/POST using JavaScript or React. ASP.NET Core MVC is a highly flexible framework that allows you to choose the view engine that you prefer. Razor is just one of the view engine options available in ASP.NET Core.

To use regular .html pages, you can create a controller action that returns a static .html file using the `File()` method. For example, you can create a controller action that returns the index.html file in the `wwwroot` directory like this:

```csharp
public class HomeController : Controller
{
    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        return File("~/index.html", "text/html");
    }
}
```

You can then use JavaScript or React to perform GET/POST requests to your ASP.NET Core MVC backend, just as you would with any other API backend.

Keep in mind that using .html files for your views means that you won't be able to use server-side rendering or other features that Razor views provide, such as strongly-typed models or layout pages. However, if you don't need those features and prefer to use a client-side framework like React for your views, this approach can work well.

One possible reason why Razor Pages may be messing with your inherited CSS is that they are designed to use a layout file that provides a consistent look and feel for all pages in the application. This layout file can include CSS styles that apply to all pages, as well as placeholders for page-specific styles.

To avoid conflicts between the layout file styles and your inherited CSS styles, you can do the following:

1. Make sure that the layout file includes the necessary CSS styles that apply to all pages in the application.

2. Use page-specific CSS styles in a separate file that is specific to that page and include it in the Razor Page using the `head` section of the page.

3. Use more specific CSS selectors to override the layout styles if necessary.

For example, let's say you have a layout file that includes the following CSS styles:

```html
<head>
    <style>
        /* Styles that apply to all pages */
        h1 {
            font-size: 2em;
            color: #333;
        }
    </style>
</head>
```

And you have a Razor page that inherits from this layout file and needs to display a different font size for the `h1` element. You can provide a more specific selector by adding a custom CSS class to the `h1` element and use it to override the layout style:

```html
@page
@model MyApp.Pages.MyPageModel

@section Styles
{
    <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="~/css/mypage.css" />
}

<h1 class="my-page-header">Page Title</h1>
```

In the `mypage.css` file, you can define the following styles:

```css
.my-page-header {
    font-size: 3em;
}
```

This will override the font size inherited from the layout file for the `h1` element on this specific page only.

By following these guidelines, you can avoid conflicts between your inherited CSS and Razor Pages layout styles.

The error message "Menu is not defined" in ReactJS is caused by the fact that the `Menu` component is not defined or imported in the component where you are using it. To fix this error, you need to import the `Menu` component from the `antd` package and use it in the component where you are rendering it.

Here's how you can fix the error:

1. Import the `Menu` component in your component file.

```javascript
import { Menu } from 'antd';
```

2. Use the `Menu` component in your component's render method.

```javascript
render() {
  return (
    <div>
      // ...
      <Menu theme="dark" mode="horizontal" defaultSelectedKeys={['1']}>
        <Menu.Item key="1">Home</Menu.Item>
        <Menu.Item key="2">About</Menu.Item>
        <Menu.Item key="3">Contact</Menu.Item>
      </Menu>
      // ...
    </div>
  );
}
```

This will import the `Menu` component from the `antd` package and allow you to use it in your component's render method.

If you still encounter the error message, make sure that you have installed the `antd` package by running `npm install antd` in your project directory. Additionally, you may want to double-check your import statement to ensure that it matches the correct path to where the `Menu` component is defined.

To make an Ant Design component's direction right-to-left (RTL), you can use the `direction` prop. The `direction` prop allows you to set the text direction of the component to either left-to-right (`ltr`) or right-to-left (`rtl`). Here's how you can use it:

1. Import the component from Ant Design.

```javascript
import { Button } from 'antd';
```

2. Add the `direction` prop to the component, setting its value to `'rtl'`.

```javascript
<Button direction="rtl">My Button</Button>
```

3. Alternatively, you can set the `direction` prop by applying a style to the component.

```javascript
<Button style={{ direction: 'rtl' }}>My Button</Button>
```

4. It's also possible to set the direction of all Ant Design components via a ThemeProvider component.

```javascript
import { Layout, Menu } from 'antd';
import { ThemeProvider } from 'styled-components';
import 'antd/dist/antd.css';

const { Header, Content } = Layout;

const theme = {
  direction: 'rtl',
};

const App = () => {
  return (
    <ThemeProvider theme={theme}>
      <Layout>
        <Header>
          <Menu theme="dark" mode="horizontal" defaultSelectedKeys={['1']}>
            <Menu.Item key="1">Home</Menu.Item>
            <Menu.Item key="2">About</Menu.Item>
            <Menu.Item key="3">Contact</Menu.Item>
          </Menu>
        </Header>
        <Content>My Content</Content>
      </Layout>
    </ThemeProvider>
  );
};
```

This will apply the right-to-left direction to all Ant Design components rendered within the `ThemeProvider` component.

By using the `direction` prop or applying a style, you can easily change the text direction of any Ant Design component to meet the requirements of your application's language and content.

This error occurs because you are attempting to use a React hook (`useState`) outside of a React function component in your `App.js` file. React hooks can only be used within a function component or custom hook that follows the rules of hooks.

To fix this error, you need to move your `useState` hook call inside a function component.

Here's an example of how you can fix the error:

Before:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const count = 0;
const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => setCount(count + 1);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</button>
      <p>You clicked me {count} times</p>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

After:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';

const App = () => {
  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);

  const handleClick = () => setCount(count + 1);

  return (
    <div>
      <button onClick={handleClick}>Click me</button>
      <p>You clicked me {count} times</p>
    </div>
  );
};

export default App;
```

In the above example, we have moved the `useState` hook call inside the `App` function component.

Additionally, make sure your import statement is correctly importing the `useState` hook from `'react'` with a lowercase "r". The correct import statement is:

```javascript
import React, { useState } from 'react';
```

By fixing this error, you should be able to use the `useState` hook in your function component without any issues with ESLint.

To vertically align text in Ant Design, you can use the `display: flex` and `align-items` CSS properties. The `display: flex` property allows you to create a flex container that can be used to vertically align items within it, and the `align-items` property enables you to set the vertical alignment behaviour.

Here's an example of how you can vertically align text in Ant Design using CSS:

```jsx
import { Typography } from 'antd';

const TextAlignmentExample = () => {
  return (
    <div style={{ display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', height: '100vh' }}>
      <Typography.Text style={{ margin: 'auto' }}>Centered Text</Typography.Text>
    </div>
  );
};

export default TextAlignmentExample;
```

In this example, we have created a div container where the `display` property is set to `flex` and `alignItems` property is set to `center`. This sets the alignment for all child elements of the div container.

We have then created a `Typography.Text` component and set the inline style `margin: 'auto'` to center it vertically within the parent container.

The `margin: auto` is a shorthand property that sets the `margin-top` and `margin-bottom` of the element to `auto`, which effectively centers the element both horizontally and vertically.

You can adjust the CSS properties as per your requirement to align the text according to your desired position on the page.

Overall, using the `display: flex` and `align-items` properties in combination with inline styles, you can easily achieve vertical text alignment within Ant Design components.

To vertically align the elements in the header and make the row between them a flexbox, you can apply the `display: flex` and `align-items` properties to the `Row` component itself instead of the `Header` component. Here's how you can do it:

```jsx
import { Header, Row, Col, Typography, Button } from 'antd';
import { PlusCircleOutlined } from '@ant-design/icons';

const { Title } = Typography;

const MyHeader = () => {
  return (
    <Header style={{ backgroundColor: '#1890ff' }}>
      <Row justify="space-around" align="middle" style={{ flex: 1 }}>
        <Col flex={2}>
          <Title style={{ color: 'white' }}>CryptoTasky</Title>
        </Col>
        <Col flex={3} style={{ textAlign: 'center' }}>
          <Button type="primary" shape="round" icon={<PlusCircleOutlined />} size="large">
            تسجيل حساب
          </Button>
        </Col>
      </Row>
    </Header>
  );
};

export default MyHeader;
```

In this example, we have used the `Row` and `Col` components to create a two-column layout in the header. We have set the `flex` property on the `Col` components to control their width, and we have used the `Title` and `Button` components to render the text and button content.

We have also applied styles to the `Row` component to set it as a flex container with `justify-content: space-around` (to create space between the columns) and `align-items: middle` (to vertically align the contents of the Row).

Finally, we have set the background color of the `Header` component to `#1890ff` to give it a nice blue color.

You can adjust the styles and content as per your requirements to create a header that fits your needs.

